    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-01-31T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-01-31T00:00:00-05:00" n="205"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d205">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">723.2515/871</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Chile</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Collier</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Santiago</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-01-31">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 31, 1922</hi>
                        </date>.<lb/>[Received March 8, 1922.]</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 75</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: In conformity with the instructions of the
                    Department, I have the honor to transmit herewith a copy and translation of a
                    confidential Note from the Chilean Minister for Foreign Affairs on the subject
                    of the unfulfilled provisions of the Treaty of Ancon, which was furnished to me
                    on the 19th[?], instant, in substitution for another communication, a free
                    translation of which was transmitted to the Department by telegraph on that
                        date.<note n="3" xml:id="d205fn3">See the Ambassador’s telegram no. 8, Jan.
                        19, 1922, 10 p.m., <ref target="#pg_451">p. 451</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wm. Miller Collier</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <frus:attachment>
                    <opener>
                        <seg rendition="#center">[Enclosure—Translation]</seg>
                    </opener>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The Chilean Minister of Foreign Affairs</hi> (<persName
                            type="from">
                            <hi rend="italic">Barros Jarpa</hi>
                        </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the American Ambassador</hi> (<persName
                            type="to">
                            <hi rend="italic">Collier</hi>
                        </persName>)</head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Santiago</hi>
                            </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-01-19">
                                <hi rend="italic">January 19, 1922</hi>
                            </date>.</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>Mr. <hi rend="smallcaps">Ambassador</hi>: With reference to my Note of
                        today’s date, No. 116,<note n="4" xml:id="d205fn4">Quoted in the
                            Ambassador’s telegram no. 6, Jan. 19, 1922, 8 p.m., <ref
                                target="#pg_450">p. 450</ref>.</note> my Government being desirous
                        of removing in the future all doubt regarding the spirit in which it will
                        avail itself of the invitation of Your Excellency’s Government transmitted
                        in your Note of the 18th, instant, I am pleased to inform Your Excellency
                        that the acceptance by Chile of this suggestion is based on the principle,
                        in its opinion fundamental, of the validity of the Treaty of Peace with Peru
                        of 1883 and of the immutability of the consequences of the War of the
                        Pacific, as has been pointed out to the Secretary of State of the United
                        States by the Chilean Ambassador at Washington and to Your Excellency by the
                        undersigned.</p>
                    <p>I avail myself [etc.]</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Ernesto Barros J.</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </frus:attachment>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
